roadly supported by those who live there; it also boasts the only fully integrated school system in the country. What accounts for the striking divergence in postwar peacebuilding in these two towns?Moore argues that a conjunction of four factors explains the contrast in outcomes in Mostar and Brcko: The design of political institutions, the sequencing of political and economic reforms, local and regional legacies from the war, and the practice and organization of international peacebuilding efforts in the two towns. Differences in the latter, in particular, have profoundly shaped relations between local political elites and international officials. Through a grounded analysis of localized peacebuilding dynamics in these two cities Moore generates a powerful argument concerning the need to rethink how peacebuilding is done—that is, a shift in the habitus or culture that governs international peacebuilding activities and priorities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational agenciesxBosnia and HercegovinaxBrčko. 0aInternational agenciesxBosnia and HercegovinaxMostar. 0aInternational agencieszBosnia and HercegovinazBrčko. 0aInternational agencieszBosnia and HercegovinazMostar. 0aInternational agencieszBosnia and HerzegovinazBrčko. 0aInternational agencieszBosnia and HerzegovinazMostar. 0aPeace-buildingxBosnia and HercegovinaxBrčko. 0aPeace-buildingxBosnia and HercegovinaxMostar. 0aPeace-buildingzBosnia and HercegovinazBrčko. 0aPeace-buildingzBosnia and HercegovinazMostar. 0aPeace-buildingzBosnia and HerzegovinazBrčko. 0aPeace-buildingzBosnia and HerzegovinazMostar. 4aGeography-Physical & Cultural. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Uni